Architecture plan for issues #51-#54

Scope overview
- These issues are deployment/web compatibility fixes for the existing LiftFuel Expo web + Express backend app.
- They should be implemented as small, isolated patches that preserve the existing API contracts and mobile behavior.

Module structure and file organization
- Frontend API URL behavior: keep request URL construction centralized in src/api/client.ts. Web builds should default to the same public origin plus /api when EXPO_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL is absent; native/local development can continue to use the localhost fallback or explicit env override.
- Session persistence: keep all persisted auth-session access behind src/features/auth/sessionStorage.ts. Add a platform-aware storage adapter there only, using browser localStorage on web and expo-secure-store on native.
- Safe-area setup: keep global React providers in App.tsx. Wrap RootNavigator with SafeAreaProvider at the root so every screen and navigation component has safe-area context on web and native.
- Auth/public origin alignment: keep reverse-proxy/public URL logic in backend/src/app.ts for CORS and backend/src/routes/auth.ts for return_to construction. Shared helper logic should derive public host/proto from X-Forwarded-Host and X-Forwarded-Proto with configured SELF_URL/ALLOWED_CORS_ORIGIN as explicit allowlist fallbacks.

Dependencies between issues
- #53 (SafeAreaProvider) is independent and should be done before final browser verification because missing safe-area context can blank the web app.
- #52 (web-compatible session storage) is independent but blocks a stable logged-out web render because expo-secure-store is not fully web-compatible.
- #51 (live server requests) depends on understanding the final deployed URL shape and should be implemented in the shared API client so all screens benefit.
- #54 (site/backend URL alignment for auth redirects) should be implemented after or alongside #51 because both rely on correct public origin handling behind Ideavibes' reverse proxy.

Key design decisions
- Do not hardcode a single deployed hostname into frontend code. Prefer same-origin /api on web, and keep EXPO_PUBLIC_API_BASE_URL as an override.
- Do not add a second auth/JWT layer. Continue using the existing MCTAI mctai_session cookie flow and backend /api/auth/* routes.
- Preserve native behavior by branching on Platform.OS === 'web' only where browser APIs are required.
- CORS/origin checks must be proxy-aware and custom-domain-safe: absent Origin is allowed, same Origin host as X-Forwarded-Host is allowed, and configured allowed origins remain valid.
- Browser verification should include root render, console/page errors, network failures, and auth UI sanity to catch white-screen regressions.
